mplex deposits","Prognosis is better than minimal change disease","Complete response to steroids occurs in most cases"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EFSGS can be primary (idiopathic) or secondary to various conditions. \u003Cstrong\u003EObesity\u003C/strong\u003E is a well-established secondary cause of FSGS, along with HIV infection, heroin use, and genetic mutations.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAll glomeruli show scarring\u003C/strong\u003E - By definition, FSGS is focal (affecting only some glomeruli) and segmental (affecting only portions of individual glomeruli)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EElectron microscopy shows immune complex deposits\u003C/strong\u003E - Electron microscopy in FSGS shows podocyte foot process effacement without immune deposits\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPrognosis is better than minimal change disease\u003C/strong\u003E - FSGS has a worse prognosis, with many patients progressing to end-stage kidney disease\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EComplete response to steroids occurs in most cases\u003C/strong\u003E - Unlike minimal change disease, FSGS typically shows poor response to steroid therapy\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe histological pattern of focal and segmental scarring, along with poor steroid response and progression to kidney failure, helps distinguish FSGS from other glomerular diseases.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Focal segmental glomerulosclerosis (FSGS) can be primary (idiopathic) or secondary to various conditions including obesity, HIV infection, and heroin use","FSGS shows focal (some) and segmental (partial) scarring of glomeruli on histology","FSGS typically has a poor response to steroids and worse prognosis compared to minimal change disease"],"references":["D\u0027Agati VD. Pathobiology 